<paragraph blockId="40.[189,1401,1957,2018]" lastBlockId="41.[189,1399,265,362]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,552,1957,1983]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippopotamorum" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,552,1957,1983]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Ebenacobius hippopotamorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[565,748,1957,1983]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished by the following combination of features: claws simple, prothorax with two dark bands on each side of the median line, reaching the basal and apical margins of prothorax and elytra with minute setae glabrous in appearance (
<figureCitation box="[1230,1324,265,291]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1853,1879]" captionTargetBox="[377,1222,265,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-15@20.[349,1238,265,1815]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 3. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 2). A. E. mulanjensis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. hessei Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. pedi Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. tsonga Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. hippopotamorum Haran gen. et sp. nov. F. E. incognitus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. G. E. oberprieleri Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. turneri (Marshall, 1935) gen. et comb. nov. I. E. rhodesianus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532977/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[522,607,300,326]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pedi" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[522,607,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">E. pedi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[615,795,301,327]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[852,964,301,326]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tsonga" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[852,964,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">E. tsonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[974,1152,301,327]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but in these species bands on prothorax are not reaching the apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[839,969,335,361]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1853,1879]" captionTargetBox="[377,1222,265,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-15@20.[349,1238,265,1815]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 3. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 2). A. E. mulanjensis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. hessei Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. pedi Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. tsonga Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. hippopotamorum Haran gen. et sp. nov. F. E. incognitus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. G. E. oberprieleri Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. turneri (Marshall, 1935) gen. et comb. nov. I. E. rhodesianus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532977/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 3C–D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,324,401,427]" box="[189,324,401,427]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,401,427]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,401,427]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,1399,447,509]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
The species name refers to the location where the recently collected specimens were found: a dry river bank inhabited by a group of hippos that made access to the flowering 
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1089,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ebenaceae" genus="Euclea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1008,1089,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Euclea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bush particularly delicate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
